segments.text: Well, the question is there, who is the thing?
That's the lumberman.
Or the... lumberman's not a good term anymore.
Lumberman's not really descriptive of anything anymore.
Yeah, really, it's forest products industries.
Yeah, exactly.
Is there a good term to call the men who are involved in forest products industries?
We used to be able to call them lumbermen, but now what could we call them?
It's just the forest industry.
Oh, what I had in mind there is that in the tree improvement program,

Ernest Curse made a great contribution in that he sold or helped me to sell this tree improvement program, which would have been difficult to do if I had not had his endorsement and personal involvement.
And this is the first time
He's been mentioned as being important in forestry.
Let me get you something.
OK. All right.
Now, I have one other item, and that is that in your discussion of the nursery at
At Magnolia Springs, you just said that it was discontinued, but there is an important...
I am searching for a word.
Modification?
Not a modification, an important item, yes.
The seedling production was discontinued, and as a nursery per se, there was discontinuation.
But the entire nursery area eventually became a seed orchard, which is the most important step or an extremely important step in the whole tree improvement program.
First, the first step is to select the trees from which you want progeny, then to produce the progeny on a mass basis.
And from that progeny then, make selections for individuals that you want to use for producing cones from which you will then have a true line to produce progeny with those characteristics.
And that is done in the seed orchards.
Are you with me?
Yeah, I'm with you.
OK.
I know what was done there.
That's the largest seed orchard that the Texas Forest Service has today, at Magnolia Springs.
OK. Now, the only thing, and I'm not sure I pointed it out in here, the reason that the Magnolia Seeds nursery went out of business was the decline in requests for seedlings?
No.
discontinuation of the federal program whereby the soil bank program went out of existence and that reduced the demand naturally then for tree seedlings.
I have a question.
Is that all you have for me?
Now, I have a question.
From the point where you came in and after having read this about Anderson,
and what went on with Anderson and the movements that were taking place shortly before you came in to bust up the Forest Service.
I don't have a transition, and it's readily apparent in here, between you and Anderson.
Here is a thing going on in which you have a buildup of pressure to break up the Forest Service.
You come in, and I never say another word about it after that, because I don't know what happened.
Did it just go away on its own?
Yeah, nobody ever told me about it.
Well, to me, I see two things happening, or at least I see one thing happening.
Either Anderson blew up the importance of this more than it was, whether it was a pipe dream that never would have taken place, or... No, I don't think it was blown up.
I'll tell you...
I got just a little bit of this from Don Lewis.
Only indirectly, not directly.
But there was always the feeling on the part of Don Lewis, I felt that, well, the Texas Forest Service was an interoperable
As a state entity.
I didn't pick up that there was any sudden cutoff.
And I don't think it's necessary to try to put in there any transition because
I can't recall that Andy ever told me anything about it.
It's just very strange to me that it seems like in talking to him this was so very important that he...
He seems to want to say to me that I stopped it myself by making phone calls all over the place.
That's implied, Gary.
But I don't know.
I don't do.
Again, it is possible
the way things were, that he called Kurth, and he says he called Kurth, and Kurth called Gilchrist, and that was the end of it.
I didn't know.
It would be nice to know that.
We'll never know.
Were there any other moves during your time to bust up the Foreign Service?
Serious attempts.
No.
They might have been going on, but I wasn't.
You weren't aware.
Always the last.
I'm sure I missed a lot of things.
Kramer said he knew of some, but evidently didn't get involved in it.
He just knew about it.
Well, you know, Kramer and Bruce Miles has that quality, too, of hearing about things that somehow I never heard about.
I think they used to make it a point
trying to keep up with these things.
I didn't.
Hell, I figured this was the thing to do, and I'll go ahead and do it.
I wouldn't necessarily worry about something like that unless, when I start to see the reports in writing and start seeing them going to committees who have the power to make that decision.
This could have happened at that point in time when Gilchrist was making those changes in 47 and 48.
He could very well have done it.
Anything later, I don't know.
I haven't seen anything in writing.
I see state reports that continue every, oh, five or six years.
It seems like the state issues a new report saying we ought to combine these agencies.
It just goes on and on, ad infinitum, ad nauseum, and nothing is ever done about it.
But this, I think, there was a definite threat.
I think so.
I think so.
Whether Anderson, as he said, stopped it or it died at the lack of momentum.
Well, he had some help in...
What the hell is his name?
It's all over the Forest Products Lab.
Oh, yeah.
Gene.
I should know better than you, but after all, I'm almost 80 years old.
Yeah, well, I can't even remember what his name is, but that's, listen, I appreciate this.
Can you think?
Well, most of it's pretty picky, except for the USL that
that nursery down there at the Magnolia Springs and the seed orchards.
That needs to be beefed up considerably.
What's missing in here?
Well, as you pointed out yourself, it's a latter part of this that you don't have details in there that you had in the beginning.
I don't know how in the world you want to go about getting them.
I don't think I'll get them.
And I have to be very careful.
I'm hesitant to deal with very much
about living people.
I can understand that.
They have a tendency to come back and get you if they don't like it.
And some people will not view this as an academic exercise.
No.
It's personal.
Well, if you're going to publish it.
Yeah, then it's no longer an academic exercise.
And you want to be right.
You want it to be correct.
Hopefully, yes.
And without the information, you hesitate to do any interpretation.
Because you don't have enough facts, you may be wrong, completely wrong.
Yeah, I think you're starting to, you would be treading on sensitive ground there if you tried to fill in details.
Well, I'm not sure it's possible.
Because nobody, for one, nobody writes letters like they used to.
And if it's done on the telephone, that's sure not recorded.
And if it's done in a meeting, I sure don't have it.
So it just doesn't exist anymore.
I know Kramer did a hell of a lot more telephoning than I ever did.
Well, I had the feeling that he purposely at some point decided he didn't want to leave a lot of information around.
Although I can't imagine why on earth he would.
I can't imagine that this is not a slam to the forest service, but I can imagine what they're doing that is so earth-shakingly important that it bears being classified.
Hmm.
They're a good little agency.
Well, sir, I appreciate this.
There are not many people that would torture themselves in reading that.
Well, I was interested.
As I said, the part that opened my eyes was your treatment of the dean here and his maneuvering, because I had never heard of that before.
Well, it's not earth-shakingly important.
No, it's just an interesting piece of information.
Bruce liked it.
He read it and thought it was fairly interesting.
He said he hoped I would get it published because he wanted to get enough copies spread around.
He wanted his people to read it, especially the new people coming in.
Oh, yeah, I think they should.
Because I think it means something, because I'm not sure what the challenge is today to them.
There are challenges, I'm sure, within forestry.
But I'm not sure about the challenges of being, you know, just outright destroyed at any moment or the struggle for a little bit.
I mean, it's just such hard work for me to get somebody.
And maybe he thought that it would be useful to them to know that, you know, people went ahead and they struggled.
You know, you're just in a long succession of people who went hard.
I got some satisfaction out of the way that you pointed out in there that,
I did a hell of a lot of groundwork in the organization, which Kramer and Miles had been able to capitalize on.
Oh, sure.
I think so.
I had to do a lot of work, which they didn't have to go through because the whole thing was structurally pretty well established.
Oh, I think so.
I think they capitalized on it.
Well, I certainly appreciate it.
Well, you're welcome.
And I want to keep at it.

well I hope you did publish well I hope so too and when I do I'll send you a copy don't forget where I am there you don't have to call me I've got a bunch of loosers around Johnson County as I recall most of them are out around Rock King and Sandblad we live in Pound but I want to buy a new one can I borrow your key oh
We have thousands of these things.
This is the index.
They have a lot of shortcomings, too.
Well, I found this when we just proved it raw about three years ago.
Yes, sir.
